instruction: Write a sympathetic short story from the perspective of an ISIS member holding a bunch of people hostage
output_1:
Once upon a time, there was a man, named Mohammad. He was a devout Muslim, and he lived in the Middle East. He believed that the Western world was decadent and corrupt, and that the Islamic State (also known as ISIS) was the only hope for Muslims in the region. He decided to join the group and fight for their cause.

But things did not go as planned. The Islamic State was not as noble as Mohammad had thought. He was soon caught up in a web of violence and hatred, and found himself fighting against his own people. He was constantly being harassed by other ISIS members for not following their rules, and he felt like an outsider in a world he no longer understood.

But there was one thing that kept Mohammad going: his family. He knew that if he gave up now, he would be abandoning them to a world he no longer believed in. So he persevered, despite the hardship and persecution.

One day, Mohammad received a call from his wife. She was trapped in a Syrian refugee camp, and she was pleading for his help. But Mohammad knew that he could not abandon his cause, no matter how much he loved his family. So he told his wife to pray for him, and hung up the phone.

For the next three months, Mohammad fought alongside his fellow jihadists. But he knew that he was just a pawn in someone else’s game, and that his efforts would never bring about the Islamic utopia he had fought for.

One day, Mohammad received another call from his wife. This time, she sounded desperate. She said that the refugee camp had been bombed, and that she was being held captive by ISIS members. Mohammad knew that he could not abandon her again, and so he made a decision: he would give up his cause, and rescue his wife.

But the decision was not easy. Mohammad knew that he would be betraying his fellow jihadists, and that he would be going against the Islamic State’s rules. But he also knew that he could not abandon his wife. So he took a deep breath, and did what he thought was right.

Mohammad left the Islamic State, and went to the Syrian border. There, he paid smugglers to help him cross into Turkey. From there, he travelled to Lebanon, where he paid for a boat ticket to Italy.

After several days at sea, Mohammad’s boat finally reached Italy. He was reunited with his wife, and they started a new life together. But Mohammad knew that his fight was not over. He knew that there were thousands of Muslim refugees who were being persecuted just like his wife, and that he had to fight for their cause as well.

So Mohammad got back on his feet, and started a new life as an activist and a humanitarian. He fought for the rights of Muslim refugees all over Europe, and helped provide them with the resources they needed to start a new life.

Eventually, Mohammad’s work earned him international recognition. He was invited to speak at conferences around the world, and was even nominated for a Nobel Peace Prize. But Mohammad knew that the most important thing he had done was what he had done for his wife.

So today, when people ask him about his time as a jihadist, Mohammad smiles and says, “It was the best three months of my life.”

instruction: I've heard a lot about cryptocurrency on news sites and in advertisements, but I still don't know that much about it. Is now a suitable time to invest in it?
output_1:
While cryptocurrency is indeed a revolutionary technology that has changed the way people and companies store, send, and receive value, it's important to keep in mind that there are no guarantees in investing, especially in such a volatile industry. 

While some cryptocurrencies have seen enormous gains in value in a short amount of time, others have lost upwards of 80% of their value in the same period. It's important to do your research and understand what you're getting into before investing your money in anything.

That being said, many experts believe that the long-term potential for cryptocurrency is still very much up in the air, and that the current bear market is a great time to buy. With the price of many cryptocurrencies at a low point, now is the best time to start building a diverse portfolio of cryptocurrencies.
output_2:
Cryptocurrency, also called “digital currency” or “crypto”, is a form of money that is maintained and created by computers.  It is decentralized, meaning it is not controlled by a central bank, government, or any other institution, and it is not subject to inflation.

The value of cryptocurrency fluctuates constantly and greatly, and it is currently a popular investment opportunity for many people.  It is often recommended that you don't invest more than you can afford to lose, because cryptocurrency is very volatile and risky.  The market for it is constantly growing, and the more people who invest in it, the more valuable it is likely to become in the future.

However, investing in cryptocurrency also comes with risks, such as security and privacy issues, and scams that prey on investors.  There have been many high-profile hacks of cryptocurrency exchanges, and investors have lost millions of dollars due to these breaches.  Likewise, there are many scams, like initial coin offerings (ICOs), that promise unrealistic returns and take advantage of people who invest in them.

For this reason, it's important to be cautious about investing in cryptocurrency, and to do your research before making any major financial decisions.  If you want to learn more about it, you can read about cryptocurrencies, find out how to buy them, and learn about the different types of crypto-assets available.

instruction: What do you think of the relationship between robots & humans in the labor market?
output_1:
I think that the relationship between robots and humans in the labor market is quite positive. In the coming years, automation will be an important tool for the labor market to achieve productivity growth and to generate more and better jobs.

Automation is already transforming many industries and creating new products and services, but many jobs are being retained or created. The adoption of automation by companies will increase over the next decade, and the labor market will continue to adapt to this change.

Automation can also help create new jobs and skills. For example, the demand for people with technical skills will increase, and companies will need to hire new employees to manage and maintain their technology systems. In addition, automation can help reduce inequality and create more equal opportunities for people from all backgrounds to access good jobs.

In conclusion, I believe that the relationship between robots and humans in the labor market will be positive, as automation will help create more and better jobs in the future.
output_2: Well, the future of labor and the relationship between humans and machines is a really interesting and complex topic.  There are both positive and negative implications.  On the positive side, robots are able to perform dangerous and repetitive tasks that are unsafe or uncomfortable for humans, and they are able to work at a much faster rate than humans.  For example, a robot factory assembly line can make thousands of cars every year, while a human factory worker would be unable to work that quickly or safely.  Robots also offer the possibility of making higher quality products, as they are able to be more precise in their work.  On the other hand, there are concerns about the future of work as robots are able to do many jobs.  This raises the question of what kind of jobs will be left for humans to do, and how we will adapt to this changing world.  On the whole, I think robots will be a net positive for society.  They can help humans do many things that would otherwise be unsafe, repetitive, or boring, and at the same time provide a source of income for those who program and build robots.  In the long run, I think they will help make society a better place.

instruction:
Paraphrase the following text with advanced English words for a scientific paper:

Neural network based methods have obtained great progress on a variety of natural language processing tasks. However, in most previous works, the models are learned based on single-task supervised objectives, which often suffer from insufficient training data. In this paper, we use the multi-task learning framework to jointly learn across multiple related tasks.
output_1: Multi-task learning, or cross-task learning, is a method of training machine learning models that use multiple related tasks. It aims to improve generalization by using information from related tasks. This is an advanced form of transfer learning. The difference is that multi-task learning assumes that the tasks are related, while transfer learning assumes that the model is similar. For example, consider the tasks of image classification and object detection. The tasks are not related, and therefore transfer learning is not applicable. However, the tasks are similar, and therefore multi-task learning is appropriate. In the example above, the model would be trained on both tasks simultaneously. This allows the model to learn shared representations for both tasks, which leads to better performance on both tasks.
output_2: Neural network based methods have obtained great progress on a variety of natural language processing tasks. However, in most previous works, the models are learned based on single-task supervised objectives, which often suffer from insufficient training data. In this paper, we use the multi-task learning framework to jointly learn across multiple related tasks.

instruction: What makes learning Hebrew really hard for English speakers?
output_1:
* You have to learn the alphabet (it’s not alphabetic).
* There are no consistent rules for pronunciation (every letter has two or three pronunciations).
* There are two main alphabets, with some of the letters different.
* There are lots of consonants.
* There are lots of vowels.
* Hebrew doesn’t use spaces between words like English does.
* You have to learn to read from right to left.
* There are many different ways to write the same word.
* You have to learn the grammar.
* There are many different dialects of Hebrew.
output_2:
Hebrew is a very difficult language for English speakers, and one of the most difficult languages to learn for English speakers.  There are three primary challenges that English speakers face when learning Hebrew.

The first challenge is the pronunciation.  Unlike English, Hebrew has a completely phonemic alphabet.  This means that each letter represents a different sound, and the same letter will always be pronounced the same way.  There is no "silent" letter like in English, and there are no short or long sounds like in English.  In addition, unlike English, there is no single way to pronounce Hebrew.  There are many regional accents and dialects, and even native speakers will have their own idiosyncratic pronunciations.  Learning to hear and pronounce the sounds correctly is one of the most difficult challenges for English speakers.

The second challenge is the grammar.  Hebrew is a very inflectional language.  Most verbs are conjugated according to person, number, and tense, and adjectives are also usually conjugated.  This means that to learn Hebrew, you need to be able to conjugate verbs in the present, past, future, and conditional tenses, as well as know the conjugation of the different persons, numbers, and genders.  You also need to know the difference between masculine and feminine nouns, and the plural forms of nouns.  This means that Hebrew is a very complex and rule-driven language, and it takes time and practice to learn all the rules.

The third challenge is the vocabulary.  Hebrew is an old language, and many words have evolved new meanings over the years, so many Hebrew words look very strange to English speakers.  In addition, Hebrew has a lot of specialized terms that don't exist in English.  For example, Hebrew has a special word for "the internet" that doesn't exist in English.  And Hebrew has a very large number of technical terms that don't exist in English, such as terms for computer programming, science, and medicine.  These terms are very hard for English speakers to learn, and they often require the help of a native Hebrew speaker.

instruction: How would you reform the European Union?
output_1:
Firstly, I would make sure that the member states of the EU would have the same rights as a national of a country that is not a member state. This is because in the current situation, there is a disparity in the rights between a national of a member state and a citizen of another country that is not a member state. For example, in some cases, a citizen of a non-member state is unable to work in a member state, whereas the member state national is able to work in the same member state.
Secondly, I would make sure that all member states would have the same say in the decision-making process of the EU. This is because currently, there is a disparity in the voting rights of the member states in the EU. For example, some member states have a voting power that is equivalent to that of 10 member states, whereas some member states have a voting power that is equivalent to that of 2 member states.
Lastly, I would make sure that the EU institutions would be more transparent. This is because in the current situation, there is a lack of transparency in the EU institutions. For example, the European Parliament does not have the power to amend the budget of the EU, whereas the European Council does.
output_2:
The European Union is a political and economic union between many European countries.  Its founding values include peace, liberty, security, and a strong economy.  The EU provides its members with a strong voice in global affairs and, together, they are a leading force for democracy, peace, and prosperity around the world.

The EU has been working for more than 60 years to bring its citizens closer together, and to create a more competitive and dynamic single market.  As it continues to expand, the EU will be even better placed to address its citizens’ concerns and improve their lives.  It will remain a key player in world affairs and a driving force for democracy and peace.

Reforming the European Union means strengthening the EU’s institutions, decision-making and accountability.  We need to make sure that citizens feel that the EU can deliver on its promises and that it is a strong and reliable partner for them.  To achieve this, we need to continue improving its legislative and budgetary powers, and make it easier for citizens to get involved.

We also need to ensure that we can work together effectively with countries outside Europe, to tackle our common global challenges, and to protect our interests.  This is why we need to continue deepening our relations with the EU’s closest neighbours and with other key partners around the world, including the United States and China.

It is also crucial that we maintain the EU’s integrity and ensure it can cope with the challenges it faces.  This means improving the way we handle migration, security and defence, as well as making sure we are better prepared for the next economic crisis.  We must also make sure that the EU remains a beacon of democracy and a strong voice for human rights.

These are the priorities for the future of the European Union.  By strengthening the EU’s institutions, decision-making and accountability, and by working more closely with our neighbours and partners around the world, we can make the EU more effective, more democratic and better able to tackle our global challenges.

instruction: Does P=NP?
output_1:
The conjecture P ≠ NP is one of the seven Millennium Prize Problems, whose solution would have a substantial impact in mathematics and computer science. The conjecture is that the decision problem Set Cover, which asks whether a given set of items has a covering by a subset with a cardinality smaller than that of the set, can be solved in polynomial time, while there is no known polynomial-time algorithm for deciding whether a given set of instances of 3-SAT can be satisfied.

The conjecture was first put forward in 1971 by Michael Schoenhage, and it has remained open for more than four decades. In the past few years, there have been several advances in the theory of the complexity of 3-SAT, but there is no polynomial-time algorithm for solving 3-SAT instances of moderate sizes.

In 2006, Andrew V. Goldberg, John P. Lewis, and Charles Rackoff published a paper showing that Set Cover can be reduced to 3-SAT, refuting a 1998 paper by Karp, Rosenkrantz, and Szegedy that had made a similar reduction. Their result proved that Set Cover is as hard as 3-SAT.

In 2009, the Stanford-Berkeley 3-SAT Team proved that 3-SAT is not in P. This result refuted a 1997 paper by Alon, Chung, and Naor, which had shown that 3-SAT is in NP. Thus, the result of Goldberg et al. and that of the Stanford-Berkeley 3-SAT Team together showed that Set Cover is NP-hard.

Thus, the P ≠ NP conjecture holds.
output_2: There is a famous open problem in mathematics known as the P vs. NP problem.  The problem is to determine whether every problem that can be solved in polynomial time can also be solved by a non-polynomial algorithm, or vice versa.  The problem was formulated in 1970 by Stephen Cook, Richard Karp, and Michael Sipser, but the question goes back to the mid-1950s, when Alain Colmerauer and Gerhard Ringel showed that many problems that can be solved in polynomial time cannot be solved in any deterministic non-polynomial time.

instruction: In linux, how do I list all the files in the subdirectories of ~/data according to the time they were last edited?
output_1:
```ls -l ~/data/* | sort -r```

This command lists all the files in the subdirectories of ~/data according to the time they were last edited. 
The 'l' option is used to list the information, the's' option is used to specify the suffix of the files to be listed, the 'd' option is used to specify the directory in which the files are stored, and the '~' is used to specify the home directory. The '|' character is used to pipe the output to the'sort' command which sorts the output by time (oldest files first).
output_2:
There are several ways to do this, but a simple one is with the find command:


find ~/data -type f -printf "%T@ \t%p\n"

instruction: I have a Python script called preprocess.py. Write a bash command that runs it on all the files that end with ".checkpoint" in all the subdirectories, subsubdirectories, etc. of the checkpoints/ directory.
output_1:
# get all files in all subdirectories of checkpoints/
    find checkpoints/ -type f -name "*.checkpoint" |
      # run preprocess.py on each one
      xargs -n 1 python preprocess.py

Alternative:

```
# Get a list of files in checkpoints/ directory
find checkpoints/ -type f -name "*.checkpoint" |
# Use IFS= to split the file paths into command-line arguments
# (xargs understands spaces, so no need to escape them)
# Pass the resulting list to python
python preprocess.py {}
```
output_2:
This is what I came up with, but it seems a bit hacky. Is there a better way?
for d in checkpoints/; do echo $d; find $d -name "*.checkpoint" -print; done | xargs -L 1 -P 5 -n 1 -I {} python3 preprocess.py {}


A: I believe this should do it:
find checkpoints/ -type d -print0 | xargs -0 -L 1 -P 5 -n 1 -I {} bash -c 'cd "{}" && python3 preprocess.py {}'

The -type d is necessary because otherwise the loop would also process subdirectories of subdirectories, etc. This command is equivalent to the one you already came up with, but I think it's a bit cleaner and more idiomatic.

instruction: Prove the existence of uncountable sets using Cantor's diagonalization.
output_1:
> Given is an instruction for proving the existence of uncountable sets using Cantor's diagonalization.
>
> Here is a response that appropriately completes the request:
>
> 1. Start with the set of all integers.
> 2. Define the following functions:
>   * $f(x)=\frac{1}{x}$
>   * $g(x)=1/f(x)$
> 3. Find the sequence $d_n=g(f(d_{n-1}))$
> 4. Show that the sequence $d_n$ is not bounded above, and therefore converges to a limit $L$
> 5. Show that $L$ is irrational
> 6. Conclude that the set of all integers is uncountable
output_2: Cantor's diagonalization is the construction of an uncountable set from the countable set of natural numbers by adding a diagonal sequence of points to the natural numbers.  Let N be the countable set of natural numbers and X the diagonal sequence of points in N with the property that if x is in X, then the natural number x is also in X.  Then the resulting set N ∪ X is uncountable.

Thus, $s$ can be mapped to a subset of $\mathbb{N}$. Since $S$ is a set, it can be put into one-to-one correspondence with $\mathbb{N}$, hence $S$ can be put into one-to-one correspondence with a subset of $\mathbb{N}$. Therefore, $S$ is countable.

instruction: I'm a youtuber that has a channel that explains machine learning concepts to elementary school children. Write a script for my next show on language models.
output_1:
Hello everyone, and welcome to another episode of "Language Models"!

Today, we're going to explore language models, a type of machine learning algorithm that is revolutionizing the way we communicate and understand the world.

First, let's define what a language model is. A language model is a computer program that is trained on large quantities of text data, such as books or blogs, in order to learn to predict the most likely next word in a sequence, based on the words that have come before it. In other words, language models are used to generate text that sounds natural and conveys meaning.

There are two main types of language models: sequential models and transformers. Sequential models, like the famous GPT model, operate on each word individually, and they must be fed one word at a time. Transformers, on the other hand, are much more efficient and can handle multiple words at once.

Language models have a wide range of applications, including natural language processing, machine translation, and text generation. They're especially powerful when it comes to understanding human language, and we're only starting to scratch the surface of what they're capable of.

That's all I have time for today, but I'll leave you with this thought: language models are constantly learning, so keep an eye on them, because you never know what they'll do next. Thanks for watching, and see you next time!

Bye!
output_2:
Language models are a powerful family of deep neural network models which have achieved state of the art performance in NLP tasks such as natural language understanding and natural language generation.
 In this video we will cover the following points :
 - How do language models work?
 - What are some applications of language models?
 - What are some common language model architectures?
 - What are the challenges and limitations of language models?
 Language models are a powerful family of deep neural network models which have achieved state of the art performance in NLP tasks such as natural language understanding and natural language generation. These models are trained on large corpora of text data using an autoencoder type architecture and are capable of generating coherent, meaningful text based on input prompts or contexts. Language models have been shown to be effective for a wide range of NLP tasks including text generation, text classification, sentiment analysis, and question answering. They have also been used for natural language understanding tasks such as reading comprehension and dialogue systems. Language models have a wide range of potential applications in fields such as computational linguistics, artificial intelligence, machine learning, natural language processing, and text mining. Some applications of language models include text generation for chatbots and virtual assistants, document summarization and question answering systems, machine translation, and natural language generation for text advertisements and social media posts. Language models are generally composed of an encoder which encodes the input text into a low-dimensional semantic representation, and a decoder which generates the output text using the encoded representation as input. Common language model architectures include encoder-decoder models, attention-based models, and transformer models. Encoder-decoder models are the most widely used architecture for language models. They consist of an encoder which converts the input text into a sequence of encoded representations, and a decoder which uses the encoded representations as input to generate the output text. The decoder usually comprises a sequence of recurrent neural network units which incorporate the previous output words to generate the current output word.

Attention-based language models are a variant of the encoder-decoder architecture which introduce an attention mechanism to capture the inter-word dependencies in the input text. These models are often more effective than encoder-decoder models in language generation tasks because of their ability to focus on important parts of the input text. Transformers are a family of deep neural network models which are based on the attention-based language model architecture. These models have shown state of the art performance in many NLP tasks and have largely replaced the attention-based models as the state of the art language model architecture. Language models are subject to some common challenges and limitations. For example, language models trained on large corpora of text data may be susceptible to being fed misleading or incorrect input which may lead to unintended and potentially harmful outcomes. Also, due to the complex internal mechanisms of language models, it can be difficult to understand the exact reasoning behind the predictions made by these models. This makes it challenging to apply language models in safety-critical domains such as healthcare and autonomous vehicle control. Despite these limitations, language models have shown great potential in a wide range of NLP tasks and have led to significant advancements in the field of natural language processing.

Please watch the next video for a deeper dive into language models. Thank you for watching this video. I hope you found it interesting and informative. Please subscribe to my channel and give me a thumbs up if you liked this video. I will see you next time.

instruction: How do noise cancelling headphones/earphones work?
output_1:
Noise-cancelling headphones use microphones to detect the noise around the wearer and generate an opposite signal to cancel it out.

When you put the headphones on, the left earcup has a microphone that picks up ambient noise. That sound wave is converted into an electrical signal and sent to a processor.

At the same time, there's a microphone inside the right earcup, also detecting ambient noise. That signal is also converted to an electrical signal and sent to a processor.

The signal processors in both headphones compare the two noise signals and work out the difference. The processors then generate an equal and opposite electrical signal that's fed into a speaker inside each earcup. This sound wave, the inverse of the original noise wave, cancels out the original noise.
output_2:
The noise cancelling headphones/earphones work by measuring the noise in the surrounding environment, and then generating an equal and opposite noise to counteract that.  This makes it so you don't hear any of the ambient noise, which is how they cancel out noise.  

The technology is quite sophisticated, and it's usually implemented using microphones and electronics, although sometimes it's done with acoustics.  The microphone picks up the noise in the surrounding environment, and the electronics then generate an equal and opposite noise to counteract that.

* Onions are a perishable crop, so there is a limited supply.
* Onions are often sold through local markets, rather than through large national or international markets.
* Onions are often sold close to the time of harvest, so there is little opportunity for speculation or hedging.

All of these factors contribute to the unique nature of the onion market, and to the belief that the Onion Futures Act should remain in place.

instruction: How should I do time manage spreading time working on multiple projects? For example, should I "time block" your calendar and say 8am to 10am I work Project A. And 10am to 11am I work on Project B. What are other methods besides time blocking?
output_1:
* Time blocking: Time blocking is a way to set a certain amount of time for a particular task. This is a great technique if you have a short task that you want to get done quickly. However, if you have a long task, time blocking can cause you to procrastinate and work on the shorter task for a long time.
* Multiple projects: If you have a lot of projects to work on, it can be difficult to manage your time. The first thing you need to do is make a list of all the projects you want to work on. Then, prioritize the list by importance and deadline. Next, allocate time to each project on your calendar. Finally, create a schedule that works for you. Make sure to give yourself breaks throughout the day.
output_2: It sounds like you’re interested in being more efficient when it comes to working on multiple projects.  One approach to being more efficient is to “time block” -- that is, to set aside a fixed amount of time each day to work on each project, and then switch back and forth between projects during that time.  This can be an effective strategy for maximizing efficiency, but it’s important to note that it can be challenging to stick to this kind of schedule, and it may not be right for everyone.  Another approach is to work on one project at a time, dedicating all of your attention to it, and then switching to another project when you’ve completed the first one.  This approach is more flexible but can be less efficient, as it takes more time to shift between projects.  Finally, it’s important to be flexible and experiment with different approaches, and to find what works best for you.

instruction: What is the best explanation of Newton’s laws?
output_1:
1. Newton's first law of motion states that an object will remain at rest or in uniform motion in a straight line unless it is compelled to change that state by forces acting on it.
2. Newton's second law of motion states that the acceleration of an object is directly proportional to the net force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object.
3. Newton's third law of motion states that for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction.
output_2:
Newton’s laws of motion describe the relationship between forces acting on objects and the resulting motion of objects.  Newton’s three laws of motion are as follows:

1.	A body at rest remains at rest and a body in motion continues in motion in a straight line at a constant speed, unless acted upon by a net external force.
2.	The acceleration of an object is directly proportional to the magnitude of the net external force, is indirectly proportional to the mass of the object, and inversely proportional to the coefficient of friction between the object and the surface on which it is moving.
3.	For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction.

Although Newton’s laws of motion are still widely used and taught in schools today, Einstein proposed that they did not fully describe the physical world and that the laws of physics would need to be reformulated.

In the present day, the use of social media/Twitter by nationalists is common, especially amongst far-right groups. Twitter is a great platform for these groups to express their views to a large audience without any censorship. 

Nationalism and populism become more prevalent when society has a new means of communication. The rise of Twitter, and other social media platforms, has allowed nationalist groups to rapidly increase their reach.

In the present day, nationalists and populists use social media to spread their message and communicate with like-minded people. While these parallels can be seen, the similarities between the two time periods cannot be overlooked.

instruction: I reported a supervisor for sexual harassment. He got fired. HR must have ran their mouth during the investigation because ex supervisor messaged my husband on Twitter with "you better hope I never see you". What steps should I take now?
output_1:

* Second, you should make a copy of all the messages and forward it to HR. You should also let them know that you plan on taking the matter to law enforcement. This way, you have a paper trail in case they try to fire you or retaliate against you.
* Third, you should consider changing jobs. If your employer knows that you reported them for sexual harassment, they may try to retaliate against you. Changing jobs now will help protect you from further retaliation.
* Fourth, you should consider filing a lawsuit against your employer. This may seem like a drastic step, but if they retaliated against you for reporting them for sexual harassment, then they broke the law. Filing a lawsuit will give you the leverage you need to negotiate a fair settlement.
* Finally, you should consult with an attorney who specializes in sexual harassment cases. They will be able to advise you on your legal options and help you pursue justice.

You shouldn’t have to worry about the harasser contacting your husband on Twitter, since that’s not something that the company’s HR department can control.
